[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Ergodic theory, like probability theory, is based on general notions of measure theory.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Its initial development was motivated by problems of statistical physics.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] A central concern of ergodic theory is the behavior of a dynamical system when it is allowed to run for a long time.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The first result in this direction is the Poincaré recurrence theorem, which claims that almost all points in any subset of the phase space eventually revisit the set.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Systems for which the Poincaré recurrence theorem holds are conservative systems; thus all ergodic systems are conservative.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] More precise information is provided by various **ergodic theorems** which assert that, under certain conditions, the time average of a function along the trajectories exists almost everywhere and is related to the space average.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Two of the most important theorems are those of Birkhoff (1931) and von Neumann which assert the existence of a time average along each trajectory.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] For the special class of **ergodic systems**, this time average is the same for almost all initial points: statistically speaking, the system that evolves for a long time "forgets" its initial state.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Stronger properties, such as mixing and equidistribution, have also been extensively studied.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The problem of metric classification of systems is another important part of the abstract ergodic theory.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] An outstanding role in ergodic theory and its applications to stochastic processes is played by the various notions of entropy for dynamical systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The concepts of ergodicity and the ergodic hypothesis are central to applications of ergodic theory.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The underlying idea is that for certain systems the time average of their properties is equal to the average over the entire space.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Applications of ergodic theory to other parts of mathematics usually involve establishing ergodicity properties for systems of special kind.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] In geometry, methods of ergodic theory have been used to study the geodesic flow on Riemannian manifolds, starting with the results of Eberhard Hopf for Riemann surfaces of negative curvature.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Markov chains form a common context for applications in probability theory.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Ergodic theory has fruitful connections with harmonic analysis, Lie theory (representation theory, lattices in algebraic groups), and number theory (the theory of diophantine approximations, L-functions).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Ergodic theory is often concerned with **ergodic transformations**.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The intuition behind such transformations, which act on a given set, is that they do a thorough job "stirring" the elements of that set.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] At the same time, these iterations will not compress or dilate any portion of the oatmeal: they preserve the measure that is density.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Let *T* : *X* → *X* be a measure-preserving transformation on a measure space (*X*, *Σ*, *μ*), with *μ*(*X*) = 1.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The operator Δ here is the symmetric difference of sets, equivalent to the exclusive-or operation with respect to set membership.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The condition that the symmetric difference be measure zero is called being **essentially invariant**.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Let *T*: *X* → *X* be a measure-preserving transformation on a measure space (*X*, Σ, *μ*) and suppose *f* is a *μ*-integrable function, i.e.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] In general the time average and space average may be different.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] But if the transformation is ergodic, and the measure is invariant, then the time average is equal to the space average almost everywhere.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] This is the celebrated ergodic theorem, in an abstract form due to George David Birkhoff.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] for almost all *x*, i.e., for all *x* except for a set of measure zero.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] For an ergodic transformation, the time average equals the space average almost surely.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] As an example, assume that the measure space (*X*, Σ, *μ*) models the particles of a gas as above, and let *f*(*x*) denote the velocity of the particle at position *x*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Then the pointwise ergodic theorems says that the average velocity of all particles at some given time is equal to the average velocity of one particle over time.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] A generalization of Birkhoff's theorem is Kingman's subadditive ergodic theorem.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] where $E(f|{\mathcal {C}})$ is the conditional expectation given the σ-algebra ${\mathcal {C}}$ of invariant sets of *T*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Let *U* be a unitary operator on a Hilbert space *H*; more generally, an isometric linear operator (that is, a not necessarily surjective linear operator satisfying ‖*Ux*‖ = ‖*x*‖ for all *x* in *H*, or equivalently, satisfying *U***U* = I, but not necessarily *UU** = I).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Let *P* be the orthogonal projection onto {*ψ* ∈ *H* | *Uψ* = ψ} = ker(*I* − *U*).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] where the limit is with respect to the norm on *H*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] converges to *P* in the strong operator topology.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Indeed, it is not difficult to see that in this case any $x\in H$ admits an orthogonal decomposition into parts from $\ker(I-U)$ and ${\overline {\operatorname {ran} (I-U)}}$ respectively.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] where *T* is a measure-preserving endomorphism of *X*, thought of in applications as representing a time-step of a discrete dynamical system.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The ergodic theorem then asserts that the average behavior of a function ƒ over sufficiently large time-scales is approximated by the orthogonal component of ƒ which is time-invariant.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] In another form of the mean ergodic theorem, let *Ut* be a strongly continuous one-parameter group of unitary operators on *H*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] converges in the strong operator topology as *T* → ∞.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] In fact, this result also extends to the case of strongly continuous one-parameter semigroup of contractive operators on a reflexive space.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Remark: Some intuition for the mean ergodic theorem can be developed by considering the case where complex numbers of unit length are regarded as unitary transformations on the complex plane (by left multiplication).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] If we pick a single complex number of unit length (which we think of as *U*), it is intuitive that its powers will fill up the circle.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Since the circle is symmetric around 0, it makes sense that the averages of the powers of *U* will converge to 0.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Also, 0 is the only fixed point of *U*, and so the projection onto the space of fixed points must be the zero operator (which agrees with the limit just described).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Let (*X*, Σ, *μ*) be as above a probability space with a measure preserving transformation *T*, and let 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ∞.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The conditional expectation with respect to the sub-σ-algebra Σ*T* of the *T*-invariant sets is a linear projector *ET* of norm 1 of the Banach space *Lp*(*X*, Σ, *μ*) onto its closed subspace *Lp*(*X*, Σ*T*, *μ*).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The latter may also be characterized as the space of all *T*-invariant *Lp*-functions on *X*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The ergodic means, as linear operators on *Lp*(*X*, Σ, *μ*) also have unit operator norm; and, as a simple consequence of the Birkhoff–Khinchin theorem, converge to the projector *ET* in the strong operator topology of *Lp* if 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ∞, and in the weak operator topology if *p* = ∞.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] More is true if 1 < *p* ≤ ∞ then the Wiener–Yoshida–Kakutani ergodic dominated convergence theorem states that the ergodic means of *f* ∈ *Lp* are dominated in *Lp*; however, if *f* ∈ *L*1, the ergodic means may fail to be equidominated in *Lp*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Finally, if *f* is assumed to be in the Zygmund class, that is |*f*| log+(|*f*|) is integrable, then the ergodic means are even dominated in *L*1.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Let (*X*, Σ, *μ*) be a measure space such that *μ*(*X*) is finite and nonzero.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The time spent in a measurable set *A* is called the **sojourn time**.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] for all *x* except for a set of measure zero, where χ*A* is the indicator function of *A*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The **occurrence times** of a measurable set *A* is defined as the set *k*1, *k*2, *k*3, ..., of times *k* such that *Tk*(*x*) is in *A*, sorted in increasing order.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The differences between consecutive occurrence times *Ri* = *ki* − *k**i*−1 are called the **recurrence times** of *A*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Another consequence of the ergodic theorem is that the average recurrence time of *A* is inversely proportional to the measure of *A*, assuming that the initial point *x* is in *A*, so that *k*0 = 0.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] (See almost surely.) That is, the smaller *A* is, the longer it takes to return to it.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The relation between geodesic flows on Riemann surfaces and one-parameter subgroups on SL(2, **R**) was described in 1952 by S.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] The article on Anosov flows provides an example of ergodic flows on SL(2, **R**) and on Riemann surfaces of negative curvature.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Much of the development described there generalizes to hyperbolic manifolds, since they can be viewed as quotients of the hyperbolic space by the action of a lattice in the semisimple Lie group SO(n,1).
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Ergodicity of the geodesic flow on Riemannian symmetric spaces was demonstrated by F.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Sinai proved ergodicity of the geodesic flow on compact manifolds of variable negative sectional curvature.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] A simple criterion for the ergodicity of a homogeneous flow on a homogeneous space of a semisimple Lie group was given by Calvin C.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Many of the theorems and results from this area of study are typical of rigidity theory.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Hedlund proved that the horocycle flow on a compact hyperbolic surface is minimal and ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Unique ergodicity of the flow was established by Hillel Furstenberg in 1972.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] Ratner's theorems provide a major generalization of ergodicity for unipotent flows on the homogeneous spaces of the form Γ \ *G*, where *G* is a Lie group and Γ is a lattice in *G*.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] In the last 20 years, there have been many works trying to find a measure-classification theorem similar to Ratner's theorems but for diagonalizable actions, motivated by conjectures of Furstenberg and Margulis.
[src:ergodic-theory/birkhoff-s-ergodic-theorem] An important partial result (solving those conjectures with an extra assumption of positive entropy) was proved by Elon Lindenstrauss, and he was awarded the Fields Medal in 2010 for this result.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In mathematics, especially in ergodic theory, **ergodicity** is a way of saying that a dynamical system behaves as one indivisible statistical system, rather than being composed of statistically distinguishable subsystems.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] More precisely, a measure-preserving dynamical system is ergodic if every invariant measurable set has either measure zero or full measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Equivalently, the system cannot be decomposed, up to sets of measure zero, into two smaller invariant parts of positive measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodic theorems relate this condition to the equality of time averages and space averages.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Under suitable hypotheses, the time average of an observable along almost every orbit is equal to its space average.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity itself, however, is not the same as randomness, mixing, chaos, or the assertion that every individual orbit visits every part of the space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity may also be described in terms of ergodic measures: an invariant probability measure is ergodic if it cannot be decomposed into a nontrivial convex combination of other invariant probability measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodic systems occur in many areas of physics, geometry, probability theory, and dynamical systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The origins of the subject lie in statistical physics, where Ludwig Boltzmann formulated the ergodic hypothesis in connection with the foundations of statistical mechanics.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity is a way of saying that a system has no hidden division into smaller statistically separate parts.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If the system is observed for a long time, its long-run statistical behavior is governed by one invariant measure, rather than by a choice among several different invariant components.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A simple example comes from coin tossing.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Suppose the same biased coin is tossed forever, with probability p of heads on each toss.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The resulting stationary process is ergodic: apart from events of probability zero, there is no further permanent statistical label attached to the sequence.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In particular, the long-run frequency of heads is p for almost every sequence.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] By contrast, suppose that before any tosses are made, one of two coins is chosen at random: one coin has probability $p_{1}$ of heads, and the other has probability $p_{2}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This process is stationary, but it is not ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The hidden choice of coin is an invariant fact about the whole infinite sequence, and it separates the process into two statistically different components.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In a measure-preserving dynamical system, this idea is expressed by saying that every invariant measurable set has either measure zero or full measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Equivalently, the system cannot be decomposed, up to sets of measure zero, into two invariant parts of positive measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity is related to the equality of time averages and space averages through ergodic theorems.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] It should not be confused with randomness, mixing, chaos, or the claim that every individual orbit visits every part of the space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Another basic example comes from rotations of the circle.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Let $R_{\alpha }$ be the rotation of the circle through the angle $2\pi \alpha$ radians.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] After n iterations, a point has been rotated by $2\pi n\alpha$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $\alpha$ is rational, say $\alpha =p/q$ in lowest terms, then every point is periodic: after q iterations it returns to its original position.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] With respect to Lebesgue measure on the circle, this rotation is not ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] is invariant under the rotation, since replacing $\theta$ by $\theta +2\pi p/q$ does not change $\cos(q\theta )$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The circle can thus be divided into smaller invariant pieces, such as $a<\cos(q\theta )<b$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $\alpha$ is irrational, the orbit of every point is dense in the circle.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In fact, the irrational rotation is ergodic with respect to Lebesgue measure: every measurable set that is invariant under the rotation has either measure zero or full measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Thus the system has many different individual orbits, but it has no nontrivial measurable decomposition into invariant statistical components.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This example also shows that ergodicity is weaker than mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Irrational rotations are ergodic, but they are not mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the measure-theoretic definition of ergodicity, the basic data are a measure space X , and a time-evolution of its points.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the coin-toss example, the state space may be taken to be the space of infinite sequences of outcomes, and the time evolution is the shift map on this space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the rotation example, the state space is the circle, and the time evolution is repeated application of the rotation.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Both are examples of discrete time dynamical systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The elements of the space X are possible states of the system.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A measurable set is a collection of states to which the theory assigns a measure, such as length, area, volume, or probability.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The space X is equipped with a sigma-algebra ${\mathcal {B}}$ of sets that are allowed to be measured.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] When X is a topological space, such as an interval, a circle, or a manifold, the usual choice is often the Borel sigma-algebra, generated by the open sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In probability examples, measurable sets are events.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] For instance, in an infinite sequence of coin tosses, the event "the first toss is heads" is measurable, as is the event "the long-run frequency of heads exists and is equal to p ".
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A set is invariant if membership in it is unchanged by the time evolution, up to sets of measure zero.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A (discrete time) measure preserving system is thus the pair $(X,T)$ where X is a measure space and T is a measure-preserving transformation.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] An invariant measurable set represents a statistical property of the state that persists under the dynamics.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity says that every such persistent measurable property is trivial: it holds either almost nowhere (i.e., only on a set of measure zero) or almost everywhere (i.e., everywhere except a set of measure zero).
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The original motivation for ergodicity came from statistical mechanics.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In classical mechanics, the state of a system is represented by a point in phase space: for example, the positions and momenta of all particles in a gas.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The time evolution of the system moves this point through phase space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Hamiltonian flow preserves the natural phase-space volume, called Liouville measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] After restricting to an energy surface, this gives the measure underlying the microcanonical ensemble.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The physical question was whether long-time averages along the actual motion of one system can be replaced by averages over the corresponding energy surface.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] agrees, for typical initial states x , representing the state of the large number of particles in the gas, with the average of f over the energy surface.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The ergodic hypothesis was an early attempt to justify this replacement.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In modern measure-theoretic language, ergodicity does not mean that a trajectory literally passes through every point of the energy surface.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Rather, it means that, relative to the chosen invariant measure, there is no further invariant measurable decomposition of the system into smaller statistical components.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Under suitable hypotheses, ergodic theorems then imply the equality of time averages and space averages for many observables.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The term *ergodic* is usually attributed to Ludwig Boltzmann and is commonly explained as a combination of the Greek words ἔργον (*ergon*, "work") and ὁδός (*hodos*, "path").
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The exact historical development of the term is not entirely straightforward; it has also been connected with Boltzmann's term *ergomonode*, used in his work on statistical mechanics.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The concept arose in the attempt to justify the use of statistical methods in statistical mechanics.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In that setting, one wants to relate time averages along the motion of a mechanical system to averages over a space of possible states.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This motivation led to the ergodic hypothesis, according to which a mechanical system may, under suitable assumptions, be treated as if its long-time behavior samples the relevant state space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The original physical form of the hypothesis was later replaced by more precise mathematical notions in ergodic theory, especially the measure-theoretic definition in terms of invariant measurable sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In 1913, Michel Plancherel showed that one natural formulation of the classical mechanical ergodic hypothesis could not hold as originally stated.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity appears in several related settings in physics and geometry.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In each case, one must specify both the state space and the invariant measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The common measure-theoretic question is whether the system has nontrivial invariant measurable subsets.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In statistical mechanics, ergodicity is used to justify replacing long-time averages of observables by averages over an invariant ensemble.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] For isolated Hamiltonian systems, the relevant ensemble is usually the microcanonical ensemble on an energy surface.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This is the setting of the classical ergodic hypothesis.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Rigorous proofs of ergodicity for realistic many-particle systems are difficult.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Important mathematical examples come from dynamical billiards, where idealized particle collisions provide systems for which ergodicity can sometimes be proved.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Basic examples of ergodic and non-ergodic systems occur already in low-dimensional dynamics.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Irrational rotations of the circle are ergodic with respect to Lebesgue measure, but they are not mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Other standard examples include the baker's map, Arnold's cat map, Bernoulli shifts, and certain billiard systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] These examples illustrate different relations between ergodicity, mixing, entropy, and chaotic behavior.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodic flows also arise naturally in geometry.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A central example is the geodesic flow on a Riemannian manifold, usually considered on the unit tangent bundle with its natural invariant measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] On a flat torus, motion in a fixed irrational direction is dense on the torus and is ergodic after restricting to that direction.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The full geodesic flow on the unit tangent bundle is not ergodic, since the direction of motion is conserved.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] By contrast, the geodesic flow on a compact Riemannian manifold of negative curvature is ergodic with respect to the natural invariant measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This provides one of the classical families of examples in ergodic theory and is closely related to Anosov flows.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Other geometric examples include horocycle flows, flows on translation surfaces, and billiard flows.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In these settings, ergodicity concerns invariant measurable subsets of the appropriate phase space, not whether a single path literally passes through every point.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In quantum mechanics, the word ergodicity is used more cautiously, since quantum evolution is not described by point trajectories in classical phase space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Related notions appear in quantum chaos and in the quantum ergodicity theorem, which concerns the distribution of eigenfunctions in a semiclassical limit.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] These ideas are related to, but not identical with, classical measure-theoretic ergodicity.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodic measures provide one of the cornerstones with which ergodicity is generally discussed.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Let $(X,{\mathcal {B}})$ be a measurable space.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If T is a measurable function from X to itself and $\mu$ a probability measure on $(X,{\mathcal {B}})$ , then a measure-preserving dynamical system is defined as a dynamical system for which $\mu {\mathord {\left(T^{-1}(A)\right)}}=\mu (A)$ for all $A\in {\mathcal {B}}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Such a T is said to preserve ${\displaystyle \mu$ equivalently, that $\mu$ is T -invariant.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In other words, there are no T -invariant subsets up to measure 0 (with respect to $\mu$ ).
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Some authors relax the requirement that T preserves $\mu$ to the requirement that T is a non-singular transformation with respect to $\mu$ , meaning that N is a subset of measure zero if and only if $T^{-1}(N)$ is.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The simplest example is when X is a finite set and $\mu$ is the normalized counting measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Then a self-map of X preserves $\mu$ if and only if it is a bijection, and it is ergodic if and only if T has only one orbit (that is, for every $x,y\in X$ there exists $k\in \mathbb {N}$ such that $y=T^{k}(x)$ ).
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Let S be a finite set and $X=S^{\mathbb {Z} }$ with $\mu$ the product measure (each factor S being endowed with its normalized counting measure).
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] There are many more ergodic measures for the shift map T on X .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Periodic sequences give finitely supported measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] More interestingly, there are infinitely-supported ones which are subshifts of finite type.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Let X be the unit circle $\{z\in \mathbb {C} ,\,|z|=1\}$ , with its Lebesgue measure $\mu$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] For any $\theta \in \mathbb {R}$ the rotation of X of angle $\theta$ is given by $T_{\theta }(z)=e^{2i\pi \theta }z$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $\theta =p/q$ is rational, then $T_{\theta }$ is not ergodic for Lebesgue measure; for example, the nonconstant function $z\mapsto z^{q}$ is invariant under the rotation.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] On the other hand, if $\theta$ is irrational then $T_{\theta }$ is ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Then any element $g\in \mathrm {SL} _{2}(\mathbb {Z} )$ defines a self-map of X since $g\left(\mathbb {Z} ^{2}\right)=\mathbb {Z} ^{2}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] When ${\textstyle g=\left({\begin{array}{cc}2&1\\1&1\end{array}}\right)}$ one obtains the so-called Arnold's cat map, which is ergodic for the Lebesgue measure on the torus.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $\mu$ is a probability measure on a space X which is ergodic for a transformation T the pointwise ergodic theorem of G.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Birkhoff states that for every integrable function $f:X\to \mathbb {R}$ and for $\mu$ -almost every point $x\in X$ the time average on the orbit of x converges to the space average of f .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The mean ergodic theorem of J. von Neumann is a similar, weaker statement about averaged translates of square-integrable functions.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] For a continuous transformation of a second-countable topological space with a Borel probability measure $\mu$ , ergodicity implies that $\mu$ -almost every orbit is dense in the support of $\mu$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Explicit examples can be constructed with shift-invariant measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The topological counterpart to ergodicity is a minimal dynamical system, in which the orbit of every point is dense.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A measure-preserving system is called mixing if sets become asymptotically independent under iteration.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Mixing implies ergodicity under standard hypotheses.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The converse is not true, for example a rotation with irrational angle on the circle (which is ergodic per the examples above) is not mixing (for a sufficiently small interval its successive images will not intersect itself most of the time).
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Bernoulli shifts are mixing, and so is Arnold's cat map.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] It is immediate that a mixing transformation is also ergodic (taking A to be a T -stable subset and B its complement).
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Kolmogorov–Sinai entropy is another invariant of measure-preserving systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] It measures the average information produced by the dynamics, rather than whether the system decomposes into invariant measurable components.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Thus entropy and ergodicity answer different questions: an ergodic system may have zero entropy, while positive entropy alone does not imply ergodicity unless one restricts to an ergodic component.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The transformation T is said to be *properly ergodic* if it does not have an orbit of full measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the discrete case this means that the measure $\mu$ is not supported on a finite orbit of T .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The definition is essentially the same for continuous-time dynamical systems as for a single transformation.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] As in the discrete case the simplest example is that of a transitive action, for instance the action on the circle given by $T_{t}(z)=e^{2i\pi t}z$ is ergodic for Lebesgue measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] An example with infinitely many orbits is given by the flow along an irrational slope on the torus: let $X=\mathbb {S} ^{1}\times \mathbb {S} ^{1}$ and $\alpha \in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If X is a compact metric space it is naturally endowed with the σ-algebra of Borel sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The additional structure coming from the topology then allows a much more detailed theory for ergodic transformations and measures on X .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A very powerful alternate characterization of ergodic measures can be given using the theory of Banach spaces.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The signed Radon measures on X form a Banach space, of which the set ${\mathcal {P}}(X)$ of probability measures on X is a convex subset.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Given a continuous transformation T of X , the subset ${\mathcal {P}}(X)^{T}$ of T -invariant measures is a closed convex subset, and a measure is ergodic for T if and only if it is an extreme point of this convex set.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the setting above, the Krylov–Bogolyubov argument shows that ${\mathcal {P}}(X)^{T}$ is nonempty.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] It is also compact and convex in the weak-* topology; hence by the Krein–Milman theorem it has extreme points.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Therefore a continuous transformation of a compact metric space always admits ergodic measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In general an invariant measure need not be ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the compact metric setting, Choquet theory applied to the compact convex set ${\mathcal {P}}(X)^{T}$ of invariant probability measures implies that an invariant measure can be expressed as the barycenter of a probability measure supported on the set of ergodic measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This is referred to as the *ergodic decomposition* of the measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the case of $X=\{1,\ldots ,n\}$ and $T=(1\,2)(3\,4\,\cdots \,n)$ the normalized counting measure is not ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The ergodic measures for T are the uniform measures $\mu _{1},\mu _{2}$ supported on the subsets $\{1,2\}$ and $\{3,\ldots ,n\}$ , and every T -invariant probability measure can be written in the form $t\mu _{1}+(1-t)\mu _{2}$ for some $t\in [0,1]$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In particular ${\textstyle {\frac {2}{n}}\mu _{1}+{\frac {n-2}{n}}\mu _{2}}$ is the ergodic decomposition of the normalized counting measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The same functional-analytic interpretation applies to continuous actions of $\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {R} _{+}$ on compact metric spaces, with invariant measures taken with respect to the corresponding flow or semigroup.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The transformation T is said to be **uniquely ergodic** if there is a unique T -invariant Borel probability measure $\mu$ on X .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In the examples considered above, irrational rotations of the circle are uniquely ergodic; shift maps are not.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $\left(X_{n}\right)_{n\geq 1}$ is a discrete-time stochastic process with state space S , its joint distribution defines a probability measure on the path space $S^{\mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A stationary process is said to be ergodic if this shift-invariant probability measure is ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Equivalently, every shift-invariant event has probability zero or one.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This is a particular case of the notions discussed above.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The simplest case is that of an independent and identically distributed process, which corresponds to a product measure on the path space and is ergodic for the shift map.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Another important case is that of a stationary Markov chain, which is discussed in detail below.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A similar interpretation holds for continuous-time stochastic processes, though the construction of the measurable structure of the action is more complicated.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A Markov chain on S is defined by a matrix $P\in [0,1]^{S\times S}$ , where $P(s_{1},s_{2})$ is the transition probability from $s_{1}$ to $s_{2}$ , so for every $s\in S$ we have ${\textstyle \sum _{s'\in S}P(s,s')=1}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The measure $\mu _{\nu }$ is ergodic for the shift map if the associated finite Markov chain is irreducible, that is, if any state can be reached with positive probability from any other state in a finite number of steps.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] For a finite irreducible Markov chain, there is a unique stationary measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A stronger sufficient condition, often used to ensure convergence to the stationary measure, is that 1 be a simple eigenvalue of the matrix P and that all other eigenvalues of P in $\mathbb {C}$ have modulus less than 1 .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Note that in probability theory a finite Markov chain is often called ergodic if it is irreducible and aperiodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Aperiodicity is not necessary for the associated shift-invariant measure $\mu _{\nu }$ to be ergodic; it is instead related to stronger convergence and mixing properties.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Hence the notion of "ergodicity" for a Markov chain and the notion of ergodicity for the associated shift-invariant measure are closely related but not identical.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $P(s,s')=1/|S|$ for all $s,s'\in S$ , then the stationary measure on S is the uniform probability measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The corresponding measure $\mu _{\nu }$ on $S^{\mathbb {Z} }$ is the product of uniform probability measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This gives the Bernoulli shift example from above.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Markov chains with more than one recurrent communicating class are not irreducible, and the associated stationary shift measures need not be ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If $S_{1},S_{2}\subsetneq S$ are two distinct recurrent communicating classes, there are stationary measures $\nu _{1},\nu _{2}$ supported on $S_{1},S_{2}$ respectively.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The corresponding shift-invariant measures on $S^{\mathbb {Z} }$ are ergodic on their separate components, but a nontrivial convex combination of them is not ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Thus it is not ergodic in the aperiodic Markov-chain sense, although the associated measure $\mu$ on $\{1,2\}^{\mathbb {Z} }$ is ergodic for the shift map.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] However, the shift is not mixing for this measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The definition of ergodicity extends from a single transformation to group actions.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Let G be a group acting measurably on a measure space $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu )$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Equivalently, every invariant measurable set is either null or conull.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The classical cases of a single invertible transformation and a continuous-time flow correspond to actions of $\mathbb {Z}$ and $\mathbb {R}$ , respectively.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The same definition also applies to non-abelian groups.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] If the action does not preserve $\mu$ but preserves its measure class, so that null sets are carried to null sets, then $\mu$ is called quasi-invariant.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In that setting, the action is called ergodic if every measurable set that is invariant modulo null sets is either null or conull.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Important examples include actions of semisimple Lie groups and their lattices, such as boundary actions on Furstenberg boundaries.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The same terminology is also used for measurable equivalence relations.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] A measurable equivalence relation is said to be ergodic if every saturated measurable subset is either null or conull.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Ergodicity also has a representation-theoretic formulation.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Let G be a group and let $\pi :G\to U({\mathcal {H}})$ be a unitary representation on a Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This condition can also be expressed in terms of matrix coefficients.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Matrix coefficients of unitary representations are weakly almost periodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] This terminology is compatible with the usual notion of ergodicity for measure-preserving actions.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Suppose that G acts on a probability space $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu )$ by measure-preserving transformations.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] The action of G is ergodic if and only if the only G -invariant functions in $L^{2}(X,\mu )$ are the constant functions.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] Then the action is ergodic if and only if the restricted Koopman representation on $L_{0}^{2}(X,\mu )$ is ergodic in the representation-theoretic sense, meaning that it has no nonzero invariant vector.
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] For a single invertible transformation T , this is the same statement for the unitary operator $U_{T}f=f\circ T^{-1}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/ergodicity] In this language, ergodicity means that the eigenspace for the eigenvalue 1 consists only of the constant functions.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] In mathematics, a **measure-preserving dynamical system** is an object of study in the abstract formulation of dynamical systems, and ergodic theory in particular.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Measure-preserving systems obey the Poincaré recurrence theorem, and are a special case of conservative systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] They provide the formal, mathematical basis for a broad range of physical systems, and, in particular, many systems from classical mechanics (in particular, most non-dissipative systems) as well as systems in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] A measure-preserving dynamical system is defined as a probability space and a measure-preserving transformation on it.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] One may ask why the measure preserving transformation is defined in terms of the inverse $\mu (T^{-1}(A))=\mu (A)$ instead of the forward transformation $\mu (T(A))=\mu (A)$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Now, distribute an even layer of paint on the unit interval $[0,1]$ , and then map the paint forward.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The paint on the $[0,1/2]$ half is spread thinly over all of $[0,1]$ , and the paint on the $[1/2,1]$ half as well.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The two layers of thin paint, layered together, recreates the exact same paint thickness.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] More generally, the paint that would arrive at subset $A\subset [0,1]$ comes from the subset $T^{-1}(A)$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] For the paint thickness to remain unchanged (measure-preserving), the mass of incoming paint should be the same: $\mu (A)=\mu (T^{-1}(A))$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Consider now the special case of maps ${\mathcal {T}}$ which preserve intersections, unions and complements (so that it is a map of Borel sets) and also sends X to X (because we want it to be conservative).
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Every such conservative, Borel-preserving map can be specified by some surjective map $T:X\to X$ by writing ${\mathcal {T}}(A)=T^{-1}(A)$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Of course, one could also define ${\mathcal {T}}(A)=T(A)$ , but this is not enough to specify all such possible maps ${\mathcal {T}}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] That is, conservative, Borel-preserving maps ${\mathcal {T}}$ cannot, in general, be written in the form ${\mathcal {T}}(A)=T(A);$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] $\mu (T^{-1}(A))$ has the form of a pushforward, whereas $\mu (T(A))$ is generically called a pullback.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Almost all properties and behaviors of dynamical systems are defined in terms of the pushforward.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] There are two classification problems of interest.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] One, discussed below, fixes $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu )$ and asks about the isomorphism classes of a transformation map T .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The other, discussed in transfer operator, fixes $(X,{\mathcal {B}})$ and T , and asks about maps $\mu$ that are measure-like.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Measure-like, in that they preserve the Borel properties, but are no longer invariant; they are in general dissipative and so give insights into dissipative systems and the route to equilibrium.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] In terms of physics, the measure-preserving dynamical system $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu ,T)$ often describes a physical system that is in equilibrium, for example, thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Often, the answer is by stirring, mixing, turbulence, thermalization or other such processes.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] If a transformation map T describes this stirring, mixing, etc. then the system $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu ,T)$ is all that is left, after all of the transient modes have decayed away.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The transient modes are precisely those eigenvectors of the transfer operator that have eigenvalue less than one; the invariant measure $\mu$ is the one mode that does not decay away.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The rate of decay of the transient modes are given by (the logarithm of) their eigenvalues; the eigenvalue one corresponds to infinite half-life.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The microcanonical ensemble from physics provides an informal example.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Consider, for example, a fluid, gas or plasma in a box of width, length and height $w\times l\times h,$ consisting of N atoms.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] This ensemble of all-possible-boxes is the space X above.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] In the case of an ideal gas, the measure $\mu$ is given by the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] It is a product measure, in that if $p_{i}(x,y,z,v_{x},v_{y},v_{z})\,d^{3}x\,d^{3}p$ is the probability of atom i having position and velocity $x,y,z,v_{x},v_{y},v_{z}$ , then, for N atoms, the probability is the product of N of these.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] This measure is understood to apply to the ensemble.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] So, for example, one of the possible boxes in the ensemble has all of the atoms on one side of the box.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] One can compute the likelihood of this, in the Maxwell–Boltzmann measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] It will be enormously tiny, of order ${\mathcal {O}}\left(2^{-3N}\right).$ Of all possible boxes in the ensemble, this is a ridiculously small fraction.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The only reason that this is an "informal example" is because writing down the transition function T is difficult, and, even if written down, it is hard to perform practical computations with it.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Difficulties are compounded if there are interactions between the particles themselves, like a van der Waals interaction or some other interaction suitable for a liquid or a plasma; in such cases, the invariant measure is no longer the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The art of physics is finding reasonable approximations.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] This system does exhibit one key idea from the classification of measure-preserving dynamical systems: two ensembles, having different temperatures, are inequivalent.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The entropy for a given canonical ensemble depends on its temperature; as physical systems, it is "obvious" that when the temperatures differ, so do the systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] This holds in general: systems with different entropy are not isomorphic.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Unlike the informal example above, the examples below are sufficiently well-defined and tractable that explicit, formal computations can be performed.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The earlier, simpler case fits into this framework by defining *Ts* = *Ts* for *s* ∈ **N**.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The concept of a homomorphism and an isomorphism may be defined.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] For $\mu$ -almost all $x\in X$ , one has $\varphi (Tx)=S(\varphi x)$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] 2. for $\nu$ -almost all $y\in Y$ , one has $y=\varphi (\psi y)$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Hence, one may form a category of dynamical systems and their homomorphisms.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] A point *x* ∈ *X* is called a **generic point** if the orbit of the point is distributed uniformly according to the measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Consider a dynamical system $(X,{\mathcal {B}},T,\mu )$ , and let *Q* = {*Q*1, ..., *Qk*} be a partition of *X* into *k* measurable pair-wise disjoint sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Given a point *x* ∈ *X*, clearly *x* belongs to only one of the *Qi*.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Similarly, the iterated point *Tnx* can belong to only one of the parts as well.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The set of symbolic names with respect to a partition is called the symbolic dynamics of the dynamical system.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] A partition *Q* is called a **generator** or **generating partition** if μ-almost every point *x* has a unique symbolic name.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] which plays crucial role in the construction of the measure-theoretic entropy of a dynamical system.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] where the supremum is taken over all finite measurable partitions.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] A theorem of Yakov Sinai in 1959 shows that the supremum is actually obtained on partitions that are generators.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Thus, for example, the entropy of the Bernoulli process is log 2, since almost every real number has a unique binary expansion.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] That is, one may partition the unit interval into the intervals [0, 1/2) and [1/2, 1].
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Every real number *x* is either less than 1/2 or not; and likewise so is the fractional part of 2*n**x*.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] If the space *X* is compact and endowed with a topology, or is a metric space, then the topological entropy may also be defined.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Ergodic means that $T^{-1}(A)=A$ implies A has full measure or zero measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Piecewise expanding and Markov means that there is a partition of X into finitely many open intervals, such that for some $\epsilon >0$ , $|T'|\geq 1+\epsilon$ on each open interval.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] Markov means that for each $I_{i}$ from those open intervals, either $T(I_{i})\cap I_{i}=\emptyset$ or $T(I_{i})\cap I_{i}=I_{i}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] One of the primary activities in the study of measure-preserving systems is their classification according to their properties.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] That is, let $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu )$ be a measure space, and let U be the set of all measure preserving systems $(X,{\mathcal {B}},\mu ,T)$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] An isomorphism $S\sim T$ of two transformations $S,T$ defines an equivalence relation ${\mathcal {R}}\subset U\times U.$ The goal is then to describe the relation ${\mathcal {R}}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] A number of classification theorems have been obtained; but quite interestingly, a number of anti-classification theorems have been found as well.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The anti-classification theorems state that there are more than a countable number of isomorphism classes, and that a countable amount of information is not sufficient to classify isomorphisms.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] The first anti-classification theorem, due to Hjorth, states that if U is endowed with the weak topology, then the set ${\mathcal {R}}$ is not a Borel set.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] There are a variety of other anti-classification results.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] For example, replacing isomorphism with Kakutani equivalence, it can be shown that there are uncountably many non-Kakutani equivalent ergodic measure-preserving transformations of each entropy type.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] These stand in contrast to the classification theorems.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] If $h_{T}\leq \ln k$ for some integer k , then the system has a size- k generator.
[src:ergodic-theory/measure-preserving-dynamical-system] If the entropy is exactly equal to $\ln k$ , then such a generator exists iff the system is isomorphic to the Bernoulli shift on k symbols with equal measures.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] In mathematics, **mixing** is an abstract concept originating from physics: the attempt to describe the irreversible thermodynamic process of mixing in the everyday world: e.g. mixing paint, mixing drinks, mixing metals.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The concept appears in ergodic theory—the study of stochastic processes and measure-preserving dynamical systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Several different definitions for mixing exist, including *strong mixing*, *weak mixing* and *topological mixing*, with the last not requiring a measure to be defined.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Some of the different definitions of mixing can be arranged in a hierarchical order; thus, strong mixing implies weak mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Furthermore, weak mixing (and thus also strong mixing) implies ergodicity: that is, every system that is weakly mixing is also ergodic (and so one says that mixing is a "stronger" condition than ergodicity).
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The mathematical definition of mixing aims to capture the ordinary every-day process of mixing, such as mixing paints, drinks, cooking ingredients, industrial process mixing, smoke in a smoke-filled room, and so on.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] To provide the mathematical rigor, such descriptions begin with the definition of a measure-preserving dynamical system, written as ⁠ $(X,{\mathcal {A}},\mu ,T)$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The set X is understood to be the total space to be filled: the mixing bowl, the smoke-filled room, *etc.* The measure $\mu$ is understood to define the natural volume of the space X and of its subspaces.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The collection of subspaces is denoted by ⁠ ${\mathcal {A}}$ ⁠, and the size of any given subset $A\subset X$ is ⁠ $\mu (A)$ ⁠; the size is its volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Naively, one could imagine ${\mathcal {A}}$ to be the power set of ⁠ X ⁠; this doesn't quite work, as not all subsets of a space have a volume (famously, the Banach–Tarski paradox).
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Thus, conventionally, ${\mathcal {A}}$ consists of the measurable subsets—the subsets that do have a volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] It is always taken to be a Borel set—the collection of subsets that can be constructed by taking intersections, unions and set complements; these can always be taken to be measurable.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The time evolution of the system is described by a map $T:X\to X$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Given some subset $A\subset X$ , its map $T(A)$ will in general be a deformed version of A – it is squashed or stretched, folded or cut into pieces.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Mathematical examples include the baker's map and the horseshoe map, both inspired by bread-making.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The set $T(A)$ must have the same volume as A ; the squashing/stretching does not alter the volume of the space, only its distribution.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Such a system is "measure-preserving" (area-preserving, volume-preserving).
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] A formal difficulty arises when one tries to reconcile the volume of sets with the need to preserve their size under a map.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The problem arises because, in general, several different points in the domain of a function can map to the same point in its range; that is, there may be $x\neq y$ with ⁠ $T(x)=T(y)$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Worse, a single point $x\in X$ has no size.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] These difficulties can be avoided by working with the inverse map ⁠ $T^{-1}:{\mathcal {A}}\to {\mathcal {A}}$ ⁠; it will map any given subset $A\subset X$ to the parts that were assembled to make it: these parts are ⁠ $T^{-1}(A)\in {\mathcal {A}}$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] It has the important property of not "losing track" of where things came from.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] More strongly, it has the important property that *any* (measure-preserving) map ${\mathcal {A}}\to {\mathcal {A}}$ is the inverse of some map ⁠ $X\to X$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The proper definition of a volume-preserving map is one for which $\mu (A)=\mu (T^{-1}(A))$ because $T^{-1}(A)$ describes all the pieces-parts that A came from.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] One is now interested in studying the time evolution of the system.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] If a set $A\in {\mathcal {A}}$ eventually visits all of X over a long period of time (that is, if $\cup _{k=1}^{n}T^{k}(A)$ approaches all of X for large n ), the system is said to be ergodic.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] If every set A behaves in this way, the system is a conservative system, placed in contrast to a dissipative system, where some subsets A wander away, never to be returned to.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] An example would be water running downhill—once it's run down, it will never come back up again.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The lake that forms at the bottom of this river can, however, become well-mixed.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The hopf decomposition theorem states that every measure space can be split into two parts: the conservative part, and the dissipative part.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Mixing is a stronger statement than ergodicity.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Mixing asks for this ergodic property to hold between any two sets ⁠ $A,B$ ⁠, and not just between some set A and ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] That is, given any two sets ⁠ $A,B\in {\mathcal {A}}$ ⁠, a system is said to be (topologically) mixing if there is an integer N such that, for all $A,B$ and ⁠ $n>N$ ⁠, one has that $T^{n}(A)\cap B\neq \varnothing$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Here, $\cap$ denotes set intersection and $\varnothing$ is the empty set.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The above definition of topological mixing should be enough to provide an informal idea of mixing (it is equivalent to the formal definition, given below).
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] However, it made no mention of the volume of A and ⁠ B ⁠, and, indeed, there is another definition that explicitly works with the volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Several, actually; one has both strong mixing and weak mixing; they are inequivalent, although a strong mixing system is always weakly mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The measure-based definitions are not compatible with the definition of topological mixing: there are systems which are one, but not the other.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The general situation remains cloudy: for example, given three sets ⁠ $A,B,C\in {\mathcal {A}}$ ⁠, one can define 3-mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] As of 2020, it is not known if 2-mixing implies 3-mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The concept of *strong mixing* is made in reference to the volume of a pair of sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Consider, for example, a set A of colored dye that is being mixed into a cup of some sort of sticky liquid, say, corn syrup, or shampoo, or the like.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Practical experience shows that mixing sticky fluids can be quite hard: there is usually some corner of the container where it is hard to get the dye mixed into.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Pick as set B that hard-to-reach corner.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The question of mixing is then, can A , after a long enough period of time, not only penetrate into B but also fill B with the same proportion as it does elsewhere?
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The time parameter n serves to separate A and B in time, so that one is mixing A while holding the test volume B fixed.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The product $\mu (A)\mu (B)$ is a bit more subtle.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Imagine that the volume B is 10% of the total volume, and that the volume of dye A will also be 10% of the grand total.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] If A is uniformly distributed, then it is occupying 10% of B , which itself is 10% of the total, and so, in the end, after mixing, the part of A that is in B is 1% of the total volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The reason for using $T^{-n}A$ instead of $T^{n}A$ in the definition is a bit subtle, but it follows from the same reasons why $T^{-1}A$ was used to define the concept of a measure-preserving map.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] When looking at how much dye got mixed into the corner B , one wants to look at where that dye "came from" (presumably, it was poured in at the top, at some time in the past).
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] One must be sure that every place it might have "come from" eventually gets mixed into B .
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Let $(X,{\mathcal {A}},\mu ,T)$ be a measure-preserving dynamical system, with *T* being the time-evolution or shift operator.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] For shifts parametrized by a continuous variable instead of a discrete integer *n*, the same definition applies, with $T^{-n}$ replaced by $T_{g}$ with *g* being the continuous-time parameter.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] in the Cesàro sense, and ergodic if $\mu \left(A\cap T^{-n}B\right)\to \mu (A)\mu (B)$ in the Cesàro sense.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Hence, strong mixing implies weak mixing, which implies ergodicity.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] However, the converses are not true: There exist ergodic dynamical systems which are not weakly mixing, and weakly mixing dynamical systems which are not strongly mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The Chacon system was historically the first example given of a system that is weak mixing but not strong mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Given a topological space, such as the unit interval (whether it has its end points or not), we can construct a measure on it by taking the open sets, then take their unions, complements, unions, complements, and so on to infinity, to obtain all the Borel sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Next, we define a measure $\mu$ on the Borel sets, then add in all the subsets of measure-zero ("negligible sets").
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] This is how we obtain the Lebesgue measure and the Lebesgue measurable sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] In most applications of ergodic theory, the underlying space is almost-everywhere isomorphic to an open subset of some $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , and so it is a Lebesgue measure space.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Verifying strong-mixing can be simplified if we only need to check a smaller set of measurable sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] A covering family ${\mathcal {C}}$ is a set of measurable sets, such that any open set is a *disjoint* union of sets in it.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Compare this with base in topology, which is less restrictive as it allows non-disjoint unions.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The properties of ergodicity, weak mixing and strong mixing of a measure-preserving dynamical system can also be characterized by the average of observables.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Since the system is assumed to be measure preserving, this last line is equivalent to saying that the covariance ⁠ $\lim _{n\to \infty }\operatorname {Cov} (f\circ T^{n},g)=0$ ⁠, so that the random variables $f\circ T^{n}$ and g become orthogonal as n grows.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Actually, since this works for any function ⁠ g ⁠, one can informally see mixing as the property that the random variables $f\circ T^{n}$ and g become independent as n grows.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The definition given above is sometimes called **strong 2-mixing**, to distinguish it from higher orders of mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] holds for all measurable sets *A*, *B*, *C*.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] We can define **strong k-mixing** similarly.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] A system which is **strong** *k*-**mixing** for all *k* = 2,3,4,... is called **mixing of all orders**.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] It is unknown whether strong 2-mixing implies strong 3-mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] It is known that strong *m*-mixing implies ergodicity.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Irrational rotations of the circle, and more generally irreducible translations on a torus, are ergodic but neither strongly nor weakly mixing with respect to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The dyadic map is "shift to left in binary".
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Similarly, for any finite or countable alphabet ⁠ $\Sigma$ ⁠, we can impose a discrete probability distribution on it, then consider the probability distribution on the "coin flip" space, where each "coin flip" can take results from ⁠ $\Sigma$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] We can either construct the singly-infinite space $\Sigma ^{\mathbb {N} }$ or the doubly-infinite space ⁠ $\Sigma ^{\mathbb {Z} }$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] In both cases, the **shift map** (one letter to the left) is strongly mixing, since it is strongly mixing on the covering family of cylinder sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The Baker's map is isomorphic to a shift map, so it is strongly mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] A form of mixing may be defined without appeal to a measure, using only the topology of the system.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] where $f^{n}$ is the *n*th iterate of *f*.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] In the operator theory, a topologically transitive bounded linear operator (a continuous linear map on a topological vector space) is usually called hypercyclic operator.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] I.e the nth image is not "too far away from", and "still intersects", the initial neighborhood U.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] For a continuous-time system, $f^{n}$ is replaced by the flow ⁠ $\varphi _{g}$ ⁠, with *g* being the continuous parameter, with the requirement that a non-empty intersection hold for all ⁠ $\Vert g\Vert >N$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] A **weak topological mixing** is one that has no non-constant continuous (with respect to the topology) eigenfunctions of the shift operator.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Topological mixing neither implies, nor is implied by either weak or strong mixing: there are examples of systems that are weak mixing but not topologically mixing, and examples that are topologically mixing but not strong mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Let $(X_{t})_{-\infty <t<\infty }$ be a stochastic process on a probability space ⁠ $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},\mathbb {P} )$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The sequence space into which the process maps can be endowed with a topology, the product topology.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The open sets of this topology are called cylinder sets.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] These cylinder sets generate a σ-algebra, the Borel σ-algebra; this is the smallest σ-algebra that contains the topology.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The symbol $X_{a}^{b}$ , with $-\infty \leq a\leq b\leq \infty$ denotes a sub-σ-algebra of the σ-algebra; it is the set of cylinder sets that are specified between times *a* and *b*, i.e. the σ-algebra generated by ⁠ $\{X_{a},X_{a+1},\ldots ,X_{b}\}$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The process $(X_{t})_{-\infty <t<\infty }$ is said to be **strongly mixing** if $\alpha (s)\to 0$ as ⁠ $s\to \infty$ ⁠.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] That is to say, a strongly mixing process is such that, in a way that is uniform over all times t and all events, the events before time t and the events after time $t+s$ tend towards being independent as $s\to \infty$ ; more colloquially, the process, in a strong sense, forgets its history.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] Suppose $(X_{t})$ were a stationary Markov process with stationary distribution $\mathbb {Q}$ and let $L^{2}(\mathbb {Q} )$ denote the space of Borel-measurable functions that are square-integrable with respect to the measure $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] denote the space of square-integrable functions with mean zero.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The process is called ***ρ*-mixing** if these coefficients converge to zero as *t* → ∞, and “*ρ*-mixing with exponential decay rate” if *ρt* < *e*−*δt* for some *δ* > 0.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] For a stationary Markov process, the coefficients *ρt* may either decay at an exponential rate, or be always equal to one.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The *α*-mixing coefficients are always smaller than the *ρ*-mixing ones: *αt* ≤ *ρt*, therefore if the process is *ρ*-mixing, it will necessarily be *α*-mixing too.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] However, when *ρt* = 1, the process may still be *α*-mixing, with sub-exponential decay rate.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] A strictly stationary Markov process is *β*-mixing if and only if it is an aperiodic recurrent Harris chain.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] The *β*-mixing coefficients are always bigger than the *α*-mixing ones, so if a process is *β*-mixing it will also be *α*-mixing.
[src:ergodic-theory/mixing-mathematics] There is no direct relationship between *β*-mixing and *ρ*-mixing: neither of them implies the other.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] In mathematics and physics, the **Poincaré recurrence theorem** states that certain dynamical systems will, after a sufficiently long but finite time, almost certainly return to a state arbitrarily close to their initial state.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The result applies to isolated mechanical systems subject to some constraints, e.g., all particles must be bound to a finite volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Systems to which the Poincaré recurrence theorem applies are called conservative systems.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The **Poincaré recurrence time** is the length of time elapsed until the recurrence.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] This time may vary greatly depending on the exact initial state and required degree of closeness.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The theorem is commonly discussed in the context of ergodic theory, dynamical systems and statistical mechanics.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The theorem is named after Henri Poincaré, who discussed it in 1890.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] A proof was presented by Constantin Carathéodory using measure theory in 1919.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Any dynamical system defined by an ordinary differential equation determines a flow map *f* *t* mapping phase space to itself.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Each point of the phase space describes the entire state of the system, typically the positions and velocities of all involved particles.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The flow map tells us how the system evolves: if it starts in state *x*, then after time *t* the system will be in state *f* *t*(*x*).
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] If we follow this point for all times *t*, we obtain the *orbit* of *x*.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The system is said to be volume-preserving if the volume of each set in phase space is invariant under the flow.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] , there is an orbit that intersects this open set infinitely often.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] We may think of the open set as tiny; the claim is that there will be orbits that return to this tiny set.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The assumption that all orbits be bounded is crucial: otherwise the orbits could "go off to infinity", never to return.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The other important assumption is that the system is volume-preserving.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] This is a common feature of physical systems when there is no friction or air resistance, no energy is pumped in and no energy is ever lost to heat.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Technically, all Hamiltonian systems are volume-preserving because of Liouville's theorem.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] As an example of the theorem, consider a billiard table (without pockets) and a set of billiard balls, moving on the table without friction and undergoing completely elastic collisions with the cushions and the other balls.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] This ensures that no energy is ever lost and the flow preserves phase space volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] We can even allow for hills and valleys on the table.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] A point in phase space specifies the positions and velocities of all balls.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] If we impose a certain maximum total energy on the balls, then the system has bounded orbits and Poincaré's theorem applies.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] It states: when specifying the initial positions and velocities of all balls with arbitrary (but finite) precision, there will be orbits that start according to these specifications and that will return infinitely often to conditions that also accord with those specifications.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Note however that not *all* orbits will necessarily return: it's possible to find orbits so finely tuned that some balls will slowly come to rest at the top of hills, never to return.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The Poincaré recurrence theorem has applications in statistical mechanics, dynamical systems, and ergodic theory.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] In statistical mechanics, it is used to predict the long-term behavior of isolated systems, such as gases confined to a finite volume, where the system is expected to return arbitrarily close to its initial state after sufficient length.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] In the study of dynamical systems, the theorem applies to conservative systems and provides insight into recurrence properties of measure-preserving transformations.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Related concepts also appear in ergodic theory, where recurrence plays a fundamental role in understanding the behavior of trajectories over time.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The phase volume of a finite element under dynamics is conserved.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Imagine any finite starting volume D of the phase space and follow its path under the dynamics of the system.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] ("Finite" here means that the volume is positive.) The volume evolves through a "phase tube" in the phase space, keeping its size constant.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Since the phase space if finite, after some number of steps $k_{1}$ the phase tube must intersect itself in some positive volume.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Translating this intersection backwards in time, we find that at least a finite fraction of the starting volume is recurring.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Now, consider the size of the non-returning portion $D_{1}$ of the starting phase volume–that portion that never returns to the starting volume D .
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] Using the principle in the last paragraph, we know that if $D_{1}$ is finite, then a finite part of it must return to $D_{1}$ after a number of steps, and therefore also returns to D .
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] This contradicts the fact that all of $D_{1}$ is non-returning.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] We must conclude that the non-returning portion $D_{1}$ has volume 0.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] be a measure-preserving transformation (meaning for every $D\in \Sigma$ we have $f^{-1}(D)\in \Sigma$ and $\mu (f^{-1}(D))=\mu (D)$ ).
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] For any $E\in \Sigma$ , the set of those points $x\in E$ for which there exists $N\in \mathbb {N}$ such that $f^{n}(x)\notin E$ for all $n>N$ has zero measure; i.e.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] For time-independent quantum mechanical systems with discrete energy eigenstates, a similar theorem holds.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] For every $\varepsilon >0$ and $T_{0}>0$ there exists a time *T* larger than $T_{0}$ , such that $||\psi (T)\rangle -|\psi (0)\rangle |<\varepsilon$ , where $|\psi (t)\rangle$ denotes the state vector of the system at time *t*.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The essential elements of the proof are as follows.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] where the $E_{n}$ are the energy eigenvalues (we use natural units, so $\hbar =1$ ), and the $|\phi _{n}\rangle$ are the energy eigenstates.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] which can be made arbitrarily small by increasing *N*, as the summation $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }|c_{n}|^{2}$ , being the squared norm of the initial state, converges to 1.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] can be made arbitrarily small for specific choices of the time *T*, according to the following construction.
[src:ergodic-theory/poincaré-recurrence-theorem] The state vector $|\psi (T)\rangle$ thus returns arbitrarily close to the initial state $|\psi (0)\rangle$ .
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] In mathematics, the **topological entropy** of a topological dynamical system is a nonnegative extended real number that is a measure of the complexity of the system.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Topological entropy was first introduced in 1965 by Adler, Konheim and McAndrew.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Their definition was modelled after the definition of the Kolmogorov–Sinai, or metric entropy.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Later, Dinaburg and Rufus Bowen gave a different, weaker definition reminiscent of the Hausdorff dimension.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] The second definition clarified the meaning of the topological entropy: for a system given by an iterated function, the topological entropy represents the exponential growth rate of the number of distinguishable orbits of the iterates.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] An important **variational principle** relates the notions of topological and measure-theoretic entropy.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] A **topological dynamical system** consists of a Hausdorff topological space *X* (usually assumed to be compact) and a continuous self-map *f* : *X* → *X*.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Its **topological entropy** is a nonnegative extended real number that can be defined in various ways, which are known to be equivalent.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Let *X* be a compact Hausdorff topological space.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] For any finite open cover *C* of *X*, let *H*(*C*) be the logarithm (usually to base 2) of the smallest number of elements of *C* that cover *X*.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] For two covers *C* and *D*, let $C\vee D$ be their (minimal) common refinement, which consists of all the non-empty intersections of a set from *C* with a set from *D*, and similarly for multiple covers.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Then the **topological entropy** of *f*, denoted *h*(*f*), is defined to be the supremum of *H*(*f*,*C*) over all possible finite covers *C* of *X*.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] The parts of *C* may be viewed as symbols that (partially) describe the position of a point *x* in *X*: all points *x* ∈ *C**i* are assigned the symbol *C**i* .
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Thus the topological entropy is the average (per iteration) amount of information needed to describe long iterations of the map *f*.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] This definition uses a metric on *X* (actually, a uniform structure would suffice).
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] This is a narrower definition than that of Adler, Konheim, and McAndrew, as it requires the additional metric structure on the topological space (but is independent of the choice of metrics generating the given topology).
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] However, in practice, the Bowen-Dinaburg topological entropy is usually much easier to calculate.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Let (*X*, *d*) be a compact metric space and *f*: *X* → *X* be a continuous map.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Given any *ε* > 0 and *n* ≥ 1, two points of *X* are *ε*-close with respect to this metric if their first *n* iterates are *ε*-close.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] This metric allows one to distinguish in a neighborhood of an orbit the points that move away from each other during the iteration from the points that travel together.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] A subset *E* of *X* is said to be **(*n*, *ε*)-separated** if each pair of distinct points of *E* is at least *ε* apart in the metric *d**n*.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Denote by *N*(*n*, *ε*) the maximum cardinality of an (*n*, *ε*)-separated set.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Since *X* is compact, *N*(*n*, *ε*) is finite and represents the number of distinguishable orbit segments of length *n*, assuming that we cannot distinguish points within *ε* of one another.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] A straightforward argument shows that the limit defining *h*(*f*) always exists in the extended real line (but could be infinite).
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] This limit may be interpreted as the measure of the average exponential growth of the number of distinguishable orbit segments.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] In this sense, it measures complexity of the topological dynamical system (*X*, *f*).
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Rufus Bowen extended this definition of topological entropy in a way which permits *X* to be non-compact under the assumption that the map *f* is uniformly continuous.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Hence it is a measure of maximal entropy.
[src:ergodic-theory/topological-entropy] Further on it can be shown that no other measures of maximal entropy exist.
